\begin_layout Title
A hybrid approach to atomistic simulation of solvation effect: interfacing
 quantum chemistry and statistical mechanics 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
AM
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
July 2013
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
As a widespread phenomenon of fundamental importance in chemistry and technology
, solvation currently is one of the grand challenges in computational chemistry.
 Steady increase in available computational power allows using increasingly
 sophisticated ab initio techniques when studying electronic and atomisitic
 structures of matter.
 Yet not even an explosion in computational power will ever admit a brute
 force atomistic approach at the macroscopic scale.
 For the specific problem of studying solvation we propose a multi-scale
 approach to treat the solute by quantum- and the solvent by statistical
 mechanics.
 The atomistic statistical model delivers insight into the microscopic structure
 of the solvent on the one hand, and relates that to the macroscopic parameters
 of the solvent, such as temperature and pressure, on the other hand – thus
 bridging micro- and macroscopic scales.
 For the statistical model of the solvent, we propose to develop algorithms
 and generic software that permit solving the Born-Green-Yvon hierarchy
 of equations for a molecular solvent, admitting a realistic quantification
 of the corresponding distribution functions.
 While any high-level electronic structure method may be applied as electronic
 structure model, density functional theory is the method of choice for
 complex solutes.
 The interface between these two model partitions will address long-range
 electrostatic electron-solvent interactions while short-range interactions
 will be parameterized by a suitable force field.
 The method is to be implemented as generic module, parallelized for high
 performance applications, like the determination of Gibbs free energy hyper
 surfaces of complex chemical systems.
 
\end_layout

