\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The environment of an aqueous solution can completely change the products,
 mechanism and rate of a given chemical reaction.
 Therefore, its computational modeling is of central importance for understandin
g many chemical reactions of organic and inorganic species as well as for
 industrial applications 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "book:hirata03"

\end_inset

.
 Timely examples are on-water catalysis, electrocatalysis, “green chemistry”
 (e.g., aqueous phase reforming of biomass-derived feedstock for non-fossile
 fuels), important photocatalytic processes (hydrogen production from water,
 CO2 conversion), and fuel cells.
 Several of these processes are crucial for capturing and using energy form
 renewable sources.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To support current experimental efforts in various areas of catalysis and
 materials science in aqueous media, computational studies are needed to
 examine/predict species and processes at the atomic level.
 The goal of this project is to develop and apply a novel accurate, yet
 efficient computational model for describing solvent effects, including
 the atomistic structure of the solvent.
 This theoretically as well as computationally very challenging problem
 can be tackled only with an interdisciplinary approach: expertise from
 quantum chemistry, computational materials science, and computer science
 is bundled in this collaborative project of TU München (Scientific Computing,
 Catalysis Research Center) and Northwestern University (Chemistry Department),
 Evanston, USA, to provide know-how in high performance computing and theoretica
l chemistry as prerequisites for an accurate and efficient novel software
 tool.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A hybrid approach will be implemented that combines a quantum-mechanical
 (QM) description of the solute with a direct statistical microscopic descriptio
n of a molecular solvent.
 The model will be generally applicable, but is first elaborated within
 the existing parallel density functional program ParaGauss for electronic
 structure calculations.
 The structure of the solvent will be quantified by a promising method based
 on the Born--Green--Yvon (BGY) hierarchy of integral equations for solvent
 (pair) distribution densities at finite temperature on a three-dimensional
 (3d) grid.
 Invoking a suitable parameterization, both the classical electrostatic
 effects of a polarizable solvent and the non-classical effects of interacting
 electronic shells will be reproduced.
 The structure of both subsystems, the QM region of the solute and the near-fiel
d distribution of the solvent, will be determined in a mutually consistent
 fashion.
 From such self-consistent treatment, structural properties of the solute,
 essential for modeling reactions in solution in the ground and excited
 states, can be determined.
 Excited state properties are required when charge transfer reactions at
 electrodes or effects of solvation on spectroscopic properties are to be
 examined.
 The demands of the project regarding high-performance computing will be
 tackled by efficient numerical and scalable parallel algorithms.
 The new microscopic model of solvation effects will supersede state-of-the-art
 continuum solvation models and, at the same time, will prove far more cost
 effective than comparable models that rely on molecular dynamics (MD) simulatio
ns with QM forces for averaging over solvent configurations.
 The solvation simulation technique to be realized in this project will
 have a considerable impact on many current topics in materials science
 and chemistry research.
 Based on the expertise of the project partners, the enhanced capabilities
 of the proposed novel computational strategy will be showcased for catalytic
 processes at metal nanoparticles in solution, including photocatalytic
 production of hydrogen from water and electrochemistry, as well as on actinide
 complexation chemistry in solutions of finite ionic strength.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Water is ubiquitous in nature as well as in technical and industrial environment
s.
 Due to its specific physico-chemical properties (as a solvent of polar
 molecules that in solution readily form hydrogen bonds), it plays a crucial
 role as solvent as well as reactant in a huge variety of processes – in
 the environment, in biological systems and in many industrial procedures
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "book:bennaim74,kamerlin11"

\end_inset

.
 In addition, the solvation chemistry of water is a key aspect of environmental
 chemistry, especially with respect to protecting sweet water resources,
 and in remediation and deposition of toxic chemical and radioactive wastes.
 With its goal to explore chemical and physical systems and processes at
 the atomic scale, computational materials science is confronted with two
 important aspects of interaction related to water as solvent.
 Its high dielectric constant, ~80, results in strong screening of long-range
 electrostatic fields.
 On the other hand, due to their strongly polar nature, water molecules
 are oriented when interacting with polarized molecules or solid surfaces,
 act as electron donating or accepting ligands, and easily form oriented
 hydrogen bonds.
 A successfull water model will pick the essential properties of the water
 in a minimal fashion: ab-initio or supermolecule approach is difficult
 to justify where a soft sphere dipolar water-like particles may be sufficient
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "warshel79,liu96,papazyan97"

\end_inset

.
 Current computational strategies either couple a QM treatment of the solute
 with a continuum representation of the bulk solvent or rely on a fully
 atomistic approach in combination with a molecular dynamics or Monte Carlo
 approach for generating suitable configuration averages.
 The latter methods are computationally quite demanding at the accurate
 QM level required when modeling chemical reactions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This project suggests combining existing computational ingredients using
 a novel method that will overcome several shortcomings of existing procedures.
 First, the new strategy represents the atomistic structure of the solvent
 in an averaged way, thus notably improving on an essential deficiency of
 continuum models.
 Secondly, a costly dynamical treatment of the bulk solvent will be avoided;
 rather, an accurate, yet efficient method is invoked which will permit
 far more realistic models than current dynamic QM methods.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Continuum solvation models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Currently, the most widely used solvation models combine a QM description
 of the electronic structure of a solute molecule with a polarizable continuum
 model (PCM) of the solvent as a dielectric medium 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tomasi94,tomasi05"

\end_inset

; the solute cavity is shaped via a prescription that relies on the van
 der Waals atomic radii.
 The nuclei and the electrons of the solute region are taken to interact
 electrostatically with the charges induced in the surrounding (polarizable)
 dielectric continuum.
 These charges are represented by a charge density on the surface of the
 cavity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "chipman02"

\end_inset

; generalizations for treating screening effects of ionic solutions have
 been proposed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mennuci97"

\end_inset

.
 The reduction of the reaction potential to the potential of a charge on
 the cavity surface greatly simplifies the electrostatic problem as there
 are efficient techniques for solving the associated (surface) integral
 equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "chipman02"

\end_inset

.
 Phenomenological corrections account for the cavitation energy and dispersion
 interaction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tomasi94,tomasi05"

\end_inset

.
 Continuum models reproduce the classical electrostatic interaction of the
 solute with the induced volume charge in a semi-quantitative fashion.
 A particularly intuitive variant of such models, the conductor-like screening
 model (COSMO), 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "klamt93"

\end_inset

 was implemented for energies and forces by Rösch's group 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "fuchs02"

\end_inset

 in their code ParaGauss 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "belling98b,ParaGaussV3.1"

\end_inset

.
 However, continuum models provide no insight into the microscopic structure
 of the solvent.
 As mean-field theories they attempt to reproduce the average effect of
 the solute-solvent interactions on the electronic structure of the solute
 by an averaged reaction field of the solvent environment, without offering
 an estimate of the effects of (correlated) thermal fluctuations of the
 microscopic structure on thermodynamic properties of the system.
 Another negative aspect is the empirical choice of the solute cavity size
 and shape.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Explicit solvation models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The weakly attractive part of the solvent-solvent interaction significantly
 contributes to the thermodynamic free energy while the repulsive part determine
s the microscopic structure of the liquid 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "book:hansen76"

\end_inset

.
 In an associated liquid like water the relatively strong hydrogen bonds
 play a major role for the microscopic structure, even at room temperature.
 Such pronounced solvent-solvent (and similar solute-solvent) interactions
 render the applicability of a continuum solvation model questionable 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "book:hirata03"

\end_inset

.
 In contrast, an approach that combines QM calculations with force-field
 based (molecular mechanics, MM) dynamical simulations (molecular dynamics,
 Monte--Carlo), provides detailed insight into the microscopic structure
 of the solvated system 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gao96,li03,tomasi05"

\end_inset

.
 Here statistical averaging entails significant additional cost, dominated
 by QM calculations.
 Yet, the results of such statistical sampling are only as good as the effective
 force field used to parameterize the solvent-solvent and solute-solvent
 interactions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gordon01"

\end_inset

.
 Important issues regarding the polarizability of solvent molecules have
 to be solved to compete with continuum models in reproducing electrostatic
 interactions.
 The slow convergence of long-range electrostatic interactions with system
 size may still require a polarizable continuum representation of the bulk
 outside of the explicit QM/MM region 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "li03"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Reference interaction site model (RISM)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Naturally, continuum solvation approaches cannot properly account for the
 structure of the solvent caused by the shape of the solvent molecules and
 their packing, or by hydrogen bonding.
 Explicit discrete models do not directly tackle the important question
 of statistical sampling.
 In contrast, statistical mechanical theories based on distribution functions
 and integral equations achieve a compromise and provide a rigorous framework
 for addressing both issues of solvation models.
 The reference interaction site model (RISM) characterizes a class of integral
 equation theories 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "chandler72"

\end_inset

 where the Ornstein--Zernike equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "yoshida00"

\end_inset

 for simple liquids is generalized to mixtures with strong intramolecular
 correlations, due to chemical bonds.
 RISM accounts for a very important aspect of interacting molecules, namely
 their shape, in terms of pairwise site-site interactions between atomic
 centers.
 In its recent form this theory handles electrostatic aspects, although
 to reproduce the dielectric constant of a liquid a phenomenological correction
 of the integral equations may be required 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "perkyns92,book:hirata03"

\end_inset

.
 The theory has been extended from radial correlations only to 3d spatial
 distributions of atomic centers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kovalenko99"

\end_inset

.
 In this 3d form it is suitable for integration with QM models of an arbitrary
 solute, as first demonstrated for Hartree-Fock (HF) calculations and a
 simplified multipole expansion (MPE) of the coupling between the electronic
 Hamiltonian and the solvent distribution 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ten-no93"

\end_inset

.
 The MPE technique reduces the electrostatic solute-solvent interaction
 to that of a few multipole moments, in the simplest case atomic charges,
 derived from the electronic density of the QM system, a technique proven
 successful in combination with continuum models 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tomasi05"

\end_inset

.
 A more elaborate coupling of the electronic Hamiltonian and the solvent
 environment may include repulsive exchange and charge transfer interactions
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "yoshida00"

\end_inset

.
 The formation of a cavity is an essential byproduct of the RISM method,
 but the burden is shifted from an empirical procedure as in continuum models
 to the (empirical) parameterization of the site-site interactions, mainly
 of the repulsive part of the corresponding force field.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Born--Green--Yvon integro-differential equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recently a new approach for approximating solvent densities around a solute
 of arbitrary shape was proposed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "jager07diss,griebel08"

\end_inset

.
 This BGY3dM model invokes the 3d Born--Green--Yvon (BGY) equation for the
 distribution function of a molecular (M) solvent exposed to a field of
 an arbitrary solute, Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:bgy"

\end_inset

.
 The corresponding BGY equation for the solvent-solvent pair distribution
 function employs the Kirkwood approximation as closure relation for three-body
 distribution functions.
 The molecules of the solvent are modeled as rigid bodies.
 Short-range interactions parameterized by pairwise force field parameters
 as well as the long-range Coulomb interaction are taken into account.
 Periodic boundary conditions are enforced for the short-range distribution
 functions.
 Long-range interactions of system replicas in neighboring unit cells may
 optionally be restricted in the case of infinite dilution.
 The resulting integro-differential equations are iteratively solved by
 extensive use of fast Fourier transformations (FFT).
 The overall performance of the method was shown to be promising, yet entailed
 high computational demands for realistic and accurate applications.
 The model was applied to simulate the structure of non-polar (CS
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

) and polar (HCl) solvents with hexane, methanol, and butyric acid as solute
 molecules in addition to simulations with the reference solvent as solute
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "jager07diss,griebel08"

\end_inset

.
 In fact, the BGY3dM simulation of a pure solvent is a prerequisite for
 other solute-solvent simulations; the solvent-solvent site-site distribution
 function serve as input to subsequent solute-solvent simulations of an
 arbitrary solute.
 In the BGY3dM approach a solute is treated as source of an external potential
 to which the solvent molecules are exposed.
 Both solvent-solvent and solute-solvent interactions are described by site-site
 pair potentials.
 
\end_layout

