\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Solute-solvent pair distribution defines the work integral for models with
 pairwise solute-solvent interaction potential.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A special case of, so called, alchemical processes, like gradual adding
 a term to the interaction potential, 
\begin_inset Formula $V(X,Y)$
\end_inset

, may be used to approximately estimate (or, rather, define) particular
 contributions to the free energy.
 E.g.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

for a small (external or solute-induced) field contribution, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}(Y)=\sum_{i}u(y_{i})$
\end_inset

, acting on solvent molecules a linearized expression, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta A(X)=\int u(y)\rho_{X}(y)dy$
\end_inset

, involving only the single particle solvent distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{X}(y)$
\end_inset

 might be useful.
 Arbitrary order distribution functions may be shown to be the functional
 derivatives of the free energy with respect to one- or many-body potential
 terms; for the single particle distribution that relation is 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{X}(y)=\delta A(X)/\delta u(y)$
\end_inset

.
 For some terms the first order contribution to the free energy will vanish.
 We dub such terms 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

polarization terms
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 if there is no net polarization of the unperturbed distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{X}(y)$
\end_inset

 for some degrees of freedom among the solvent parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Here we assume that parameters of a solvent molecule, 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, include some 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

polarization vector
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 No net polarization in distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{X}(y)$
\end_inset

 amounts to its factual independence of these polarization parameters.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In this case a higher order thermodynamic perturbation will define the
 leading free energy term, see below.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us examine the special case of a pairwise solute-solvent interaction
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}(X,Y)=\sum_{i}u_{X}(y_{i})
\]

\end_inset

defining the interface between two subsystems in the potential function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{\lambda}(X,Y)=E(X)+\lambda U_{1}(X,Y)+U_{2}(Y).
\]

\end_inset

Here we augmented the list of system parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by the magnitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 of the pairwise solute-solvent interaction 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Free energy 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\lambda}(X)$
\end_inset

 for zero coupling parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

 is a sum of solute and solvent energies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{0}(X)=E(X)-\beta^{-1}\ln\int\mathrm{e}^{-\beta U_{2}(Y)}dY
\]

\end_inset

with partition function of the pure solvent independent of solute parameters
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Thermodynamic integration for an alchemical process of varying interaction
 strength from 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

 suggests the expression for the conformation free energy difference with
 respect to the non-interacting solute and solvent,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{1}(X)-A_{0}(X)=\int_{0}^{1}d\lambda\int u_{X}(y)\rho_{\lambda X}(y)dy,
\]

\end_inset

which involves only the first order solvent (conditional) distribution function
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\lambda X}(y)$
\end_inset

.
 A formal consequence of this relation is that being able to determine the
 first-order distribution function, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\lambda X}(y)$
\end_inset

, of a solvent exposed to an arbitrary (or arbitrarily strong) field, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{X}(y)$
\end_inset

, is formally sufficient for determining solvation free energy of any solute
 conformation 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 This statement also holds for the free energy differences of two conformations,
 
\begin_inset Formula $A(X_{1})-A(X_{0})$
\end_inset

, that can be implemented either as an alchemical process of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

blending in- and out
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

