\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pmf-path-integral"

\end_inset

).
 Both are the consequences of the pairwise solute-solvent interaction model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For thermodynamic processes where the dependence of the density distribution
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\lambda X}(y)$
\end_inset

 on the progress parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is known to be e.g.
 a low order polynomial, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{\lambda X}(y)=(1-\lambda)\rho_{0X}(y)+\lambda\rho_{1X}(y)
\]

\end_inset

with accessible first- (or higher) order response terms the integration
 over progress parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 can be performed analytically: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta A(X)=\int u_{X}(y)\rho_{0.5X}(y)dy,\quad\rho_{0.5X}(y)=\frac{1}{2}[\rho_{0X}(y)+\rho_{1X}(y)]
\]

\end_inset

For linear response the work integral is thus a functional of unperturbed
 density distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{0X}(y)$
\end_inset

 and interacting density distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1X}(y)$
\end_inset

 only, or, equivalently, it is a functional of a single density distribution
 halfway along the process path.
 Of course, some thermodynamic processes like, cavity formation, that may
 be considered as an alchemical process of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

turning on
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the repulsive branch of solute-solvent interaction potential, may not be
 suitable for linear response description.
 The well established PCM models, for example, address the cavity formation
 work by phenomenological terms based on a simplified cavity shape description.
 In general, a higher order specialized numerical quadrature may be required
 for such processes; the choice of integration path, including the reference
 (initial) state may also play an important role.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Applying the above alchemical process to a perturbation by a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

polarization
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 term 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}(y)$
\end_inset

 and expanding the density distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\lambda X}(y)$
\end_inset

 to first order (thus assuming linear response) one obtains for the free
 energy differences an approximate expression
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta A(X)=\frac{1}{2}\int u_{1}(y)\rho_{1X}(y)dy=\frac{1}{2}\int u_{1}(y)[\rho_{1X}(y)-\rho_{0X}(y)]dy.
\]

\end_inset

which can be viewed as a functional of interacting density distribution
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1X}(y)$
\end_inset

 only.
 Here we used our definition of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

polarization
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 contribution implying the vanishing first-order term, 
\begin_inset Formula $\int u_{1}(y)\rho_{0X}(y)dy=0$
\end_inset

.
 The two relevant differences between confusingly similarly looking first-
 and second-order terms is the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 in the latter and the use of unperturbed distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{0X}(y)$
\end_inset

 vs.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

polarized
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1X}(y)$
\end_inset

.
 By using a more explicit expression for density response, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1X}(y)-\rho_{0X}(y)$
\end_inset

, one arrives at another form of the second order term 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "book:landauV5"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta A(X)\approx-\frac{\beta}{2}\int u_{1}^{2}(y)\rho_{0X}(y)dy=-\frac{\beta}{2}\left\langle u_{1}^{2}\right\rangle _{X},
\]

\end_inset

that makes the negative sign of the leading polarization contribution obvious.
 The sign and the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 in the second order term have the same origin as the those in the Born
 model for a free energy of a charge 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 in a spherical cavity of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 in dielectric medium with permittivity 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "onsager36"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta A=-\frac{\epsilon-1}{\epsilon}\frac{Q^{2}}{2R}
\]

\end_inset

that is only a half of the electrostatic interaction energy of the charge
 with the negative induced surface charge density.
 Naturally this is also how many PCM models treat the medium polarization
 contribution to the free energy, thus assuming the linear response of the
 medium to electric field 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tomasi94,tomasi05"

\end_inset

.
 Again the linear response assumption may hold to a different extent for
 orientational component of polarizability of a polar solvent and its electronic
 polarizability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary, with a pairwise solute-solvent interaction model, the single
 particle distribution function of the solvent in an arbitrary external-
 or solute-induced field may serve as a basis to built free energy functional
 of a solute.
 Thermodynamic perturbation theory offers a viable approach to construct
 free energy functionals for solute-solvent and solvent-solvent interactions
 that are too cumbersome too apply self-consistently including treatment
 of the attractive hydrogen bonds that are responsible for the structure
 of the liquid water 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "zhou09"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Liquid free-energy density functionals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Free energy density functional theory for liquids offers approximate functionals
 to be used in a minimization procedure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A distinctive approach to the free energy of a liquid is a density functional
 approach where the intrinsic free energy is a functional, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}[\rho(y)]$
\end_inset

, of the first-order distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(y)$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "lebowitz63,ebner76,saam77"

\end_inset

 including non-uniform polyatomic liquids 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "chandler86"

\end_inset

.
 The DFT for electron 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gas
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in external fields at finite temperatures and DFT for liquids share the
 same philosophy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mermin65"

\end_inset

.
 As with the electronic density function theory the actual problem is to
 design a suitable model for the functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 The singularity in the repulsive branch of solvent-solvent interactions
 makes the hard sphere liquid and the corresponding functionals 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rosenfeld97,rosenfeld98"

\end_inset

 serve as a natural starting point to develop free energy functional for
 soft interactions by thermodynamic perturbation theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "zhou09"

\end_inset

.
 A series of approaches to the functionals exists in the literature starting
 with LDA, functionals based on a smoothed density 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tarazona85"

\end_inset

 or generalized measures of density distributions
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rosenfeld97"

\end_inset

, gradient approximations, and functionals depending on correlation functions
 of the uniform liquid as an input 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ebner76,ebner77"

\end_inset

.
 The density functional approach may be extended to dynamic phenomena 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "marconi99"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A common partition of the functional
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}[\rho]=\mathcal{F}_{\text{id}}[\rho]+\Delta\mathcal{F}_{\text{rep}}[\rho]+\Delta\mathcal{F}_{\text{attr}}[\rho]
\]

\end_inset

with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ideal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 liquid contribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\text{id}}$
\end_inset

 which is a free energy of the reference non-interacting liquid in an effective
 field, the repulsive contribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\mathcal{F}_{\text{rep}}$
\end_inset

 often approximated or rather defined by the hard sphere model and soft
 attraction contribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\mathcal{F}_{\text{attr}}$
\end_inset

 approximating the rest of the functional.
 The free energy of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ideal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 liquid without internal degrees of freedom is proportional to the entropy
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta\mathcal{F}_{\text{id}}[\rho]=\beta^{-1}\int\rho(y)\ln\rho(y)dy,
\]

\end_inset

which is a local functional.
 The repulsive hard sphere contribution may be defined using (one or more)
 measures of the density distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta\mathcal{F}_{\text{rep}}[\rho]=\beta^{-1}\int\rho(y)f_{\text{rep}}(\eta(y))dy,\quad\eta(y)=\int w(y,y^{\prime})\rho(y^{\prime})dy^{\prime}
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 being e.g.
 a packing fraction of the hard spheres averaged over molecular volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(y,y^{\prime})$
\end_inset

 is often chosen to be significantly different from zero in the region 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{\prime}\approx y$
\end_inset

 on the scale of molecular size 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, such as a spherical Heaviside step function.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\text{rep}}(\eta)$
\end_inset

 may be approximated by a rational function for the case of the measure
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 being the packing fraction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "carnahan70"

\end_inset

.
 Due to non-local (but usually short-range) dependence of the measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\eta[\rho]$
\end_inset

 on distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 the free energy functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\text{rep}}$
\end_inset

 is non-local.
 A rough estimate of the free energy functional responsible for the attractive
 interaction is given by an integral
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta\mathcal{F}_{\text{attr}}[\rho]=\frac{1}{2}\iint\rho(y)u_{2}(y,y^{\prime})\rho(y^{\prime})dydy^{\prime}
\]

\end_inset

with interaction potential 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}(y,y^{\prime})$
\end_inset

 simplified to a short range square well potential characterized by its
 depth and width chosen to simulate hydrogen bonding 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "paramonov05"

\end_inset

.
 This form of attractive contribution is non-local as well.
 For the bulk liquid the relation between the uniform density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and the free energy (density) establishes an equation of state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the presence of external (solute) field 
\begin_inset Formula $u(y)$
\end_inset

 the functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega[\rho(y)]$
\end_inset

 to be minimized at constant temperature and chemical potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 consists of two terms,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Omega[\rho(y)]=\mathcal{F}[\rho(y)]+\int\rho(y)[u(y)-\mu]dy,
\]

\end_inset

where the intrinsic free energy functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}[\rho]$
\end_inset

, e.g.
 defined as above, is independent of external field 
\begin_inset Formula $u(y)$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding Lagrange equation for the density minimizing the free
 energy functional 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\delta\mathcal{F}[\rho]}{\delta\rho(y)}+u(y)=\mu
\]

\end_inset

is a nonlinear integral equation and is usually solved iteratively 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tarazona85,paramonov05"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A non-local functional for water-like fluid with hard core and a square
 well attractive potential simulating hydrogen bonds 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "paramonov05"

\end_inset

 is capable of reproducing essential features of non-uniform density distributio
n in proximity of nano-scale asperity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "book:bennaim74,jang04"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some of the density functionals rely on the properties of the uniform liquid
 as an input.
 These properties will need to be derived independently, e.g.
 by solving the Percus--Yevick equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "percus58"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Electronic degrees of freedom (slippery ground)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Free energy on ground state PES vs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

minimum of the free-energy density functional.
 Or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ground state
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

mean field
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is nonsense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The two types of solute degrees of freedom, the electronic state 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and nuclear coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 require quite a different treatment justified by Born-Oppenheimer (BO)
 approximation.
 BO approximation assumes that electronic spectrum may be obtained for each
 configuration of the nuclei, this includes both solute- and solvent coordinates
, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We do not assume the solvent description includes 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fast
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 electronic degrees of freedom.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E=E[n,R,Y]
\]

\end_inset

It is a common approximation to exclude excited electronic states from statistic
al sums as electronic excitation energies are often far above the temperature
 range one is interested in.
 The ground state energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}(R,Y)$
\end_inset

 is then what is usually used as a PES 
\begin_inset Formula $V(R,Y)$
\end_inset

, a function of nuclear- and solvent coordinates only, for exploration.
 In this approach solute parameters reduce to nuclear coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $X=R$
\end_inset

.
 Unless the electronic wave function is unaffected by solvent configuration
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, using the ground state energy 
\begin_inset Formula $V(R,Y)=E_{0}(R,Y)$
\end_inset

 as a PES implies an expensive wave function computation for each PES evaluation.
 The sampling approach would imply doing a wavefunciton calculation for
 each ensemble sample.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, when introducing the conformation free energy 
\begin_inset Formula $A(X)$
\end_inset

 of the solute in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:free-energy-surface"

\end_inset

 we formally performed ensemble averaging over solvent degrees of freedom
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 keeping (all of) the solute degrees of freedom 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (including electronic ones) fixed, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:conformation-free-energy"

\end_inset

.
 This averaging (integration) over solvent coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 for specific values of solute parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 introduced above in definition of the free solute energy should be thus
 interpreted as an energy of a fixed electronic state 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 in a mean field of the solvent since the solute parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by definition include the electronic degrees of freedom: 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(n,R)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The state 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 need not to be the ground state of any particular arrangement 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,Y)$
\end_inset

.
 Also think of Markus theory.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This recipe establishes an (conformation free) energy as a functional of
 density.
 However the minima of this functional should not be interpreted as ground
 states --- they do not even correspond to any specific arrangement 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 of the solvent.
 The reasoning is the same as for the minimum on the free-energy surface
 that should be interpreted as the 
\emph on
expectation value
\emph default
 of free-energy parameters or loosely speaking the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

most probable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 conformation as opposed to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lowest energy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 conformation.
 In this context it is probably worth noting that an expectation value,
 in general, does not correspond to any state of the ensemble which is common
 for discrete ensembles.
 By analogy, the only reasonable objective for a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

free-energy density functional
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can only be the 
\emph on
expectation
\emph default
 for the electronic state (density), not the ground state.
 This point of view parallels ensemble density functional theory that targets
 the energy functional as a functional of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

average
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 density (density matrix) and formally requires adapted QM energy functionals,
 though the functionals designed for ground state are often used in practice.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This second point of view is assumed below when discussing thermodynamic
 averaging of solute-solvent electrostatic interactions with a fixed solute
 charge distribution.
 We do not (yet) discuss availability of specialized 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

free energy density functionals
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 thus also making a (questionable) assumption that the conventional ground
 state DFT functionals may be reused.
 Again the typical energy separations between the ground and excited electronic
 states that at low temperatures usually imply that the 
\emph on
expectation
\emph default
 is close to the 
\emph on
ground
\emph default
 state may serve as an intuitive justification of the ground state DFT abuse.
 Note that this very assumption is made in many continuum solvent models
 targeting the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ground electronic state
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the mean field of the solvent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Interfacing solute and solvent 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:interface"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Simplified intermediate density representation in definition of solute-solvent
 interaction may make the latter faster to evaluate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Irrespective of the approach used to address the conditional solvent distributio
n function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(X,Y)$
\end_inset

 for some specific conformation of the solute 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 one has to propose a suitable model of the interaction of the solute and
 solvent molecules summarized in the function 
\begin_inset Formula $V(X,Y)$
\end_inset

.
 A successful interaction model will allow an efficient computation of the
 potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(X,Y)$
\end_inset

 for many solvent configurations 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 with solute parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 being fixed.
 Note that in a hybrid QM/solvent model evaluation of the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(X,Y)$
\end_inset

 for several values of solute coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 necessarily will require an expensive QM calculation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest approach for constructing such a model is to reduce the potential
 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to a sum of QM ground state energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}$
\end_inset

 as a function of solute geometry 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and a force-field potential 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(R,Y)=E_{0}(R)+U(R,Y)
\]

\end_inset

This amounts to an (admittedly strong) assumption that electronic wave function
 is independent of solvent arrangement.
 In particular this form does not cover electrostatic Coulomb interaction
 of electron- and solvent charge distribution densities.
 A simple form of force-field potential 
\begin_inset Formula $U(R,Y)$
\end_inset

 will allow efficient sampling/integration over solvent coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More useful approach will account for interaction of electronic degrees
 of freedom 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, which, in DFT spirit, will be interpreted as electronic density from now
 on and solvent degrees of freedom 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 A successful approach accounting for this kind of interaction will need
 to allow efficient evaluations of energy functional
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(X,Y)\equiv V[n,R,Y]
\]

\end_inset

with a fixed solute state, parametrized by electronic density 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and geometry 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, for sufficiently many solvent configurations 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To achieve this goal the original RISM formulation proposed to reduce the
 representation of the electronic density 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 to a set of point charges 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 centered at positions of solute atoms 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 by a procedure similar to the one used for population analysis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ten-no93"

\end_inset

.
 The total energy of the system is then defined as a functional
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V[n,R,Y]=E[n,R]+U(Q[n],R,Y)
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $E[n,R]$
\end_inset

 being the reference (e.g.
 Kohn--Sham) energy functional of the solute and the interaction 
\begin_inset Formula $U(Q,R,Y)$
\end_inset

 has a form of a force-field that includes the Coulomb interaction of solute
 and solvent charges.
 For any particular solvent configuration 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 the solvent-induced contribution will affect the minimization procedure
 of the total energy functional, 
\begin_inset Formula $V[n,R,Y]$
\end_inset

, with respect to electronic degrees of freedom 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 (for example in DFT framework) --- the effective (Kohn--Sham) Hamiltonian
 contains, in addition to the traditional terms originating from the reference
 functional 
\begin_inset Formula $E[n,R]$
\end_inset

, the potential contribution 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u(\vec{r})=\frac{\delta U}{\delta n(\vec{r})}=\frac{\partial U}{\partial Q}\frac{\delta Q}{\delta n(\vec{r})}\label{eq:ks-q-term}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Similarly the free energy (mean field) functional
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A[n,R]=-\beta^{-1}\ln\int\mathrm{e}^{\beta(A-V[n,R,Y])}dY
\]

\end_inset

 or a finite ensemble approximation to that acquires solvent induced terms
 depending on the electron density 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The approximation the original RISM paper 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ten-no93"

\end_inset

 made for simplifying the solute-solvent interaction may be relaxed without
 sacrificing the idea behind it.
 Established procedures such as multipole (MP) expansion or density fitting
 are successfully used to reduce complexity of representing the electron
 density of a QM subsystem keeping the ability to (approximately) reproduce
 an essential effect of the electron charge distribution --- its electrostatic
 field in a solvent accessible volume.
 In both cases the electron density is represented by a set of parameters
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q[n]$
\end_inset

, either the multipole expansion coefficients or density expansion coefficients
 derived by a deterministic procedure from the electronic density 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 There is no good reason why the functional 
\begin_inset Formula $Q[n]$
\end_inset

 should not be a linear functional so that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q[n+\delta n]=Q[n]+Q[\delta n]$
\end_inset

 always holds.
 It is indeed the case for multipole expansions and (unconstrained) density
 fitting techniques.
 The linearity condition simplifies computing the response of the density
 parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta Q/\delta n(\vec{r})$
\end_inset

 making this quantity independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 For grid-based techniques that rely on Fourier transformations the intermediate
 representation of the solute charge density, that is a superposition of
 electron and nuclear charge densities, may take responsibility for eliminating
 singularities in Coulomb potential.
 These singularities are localized around solute nuclei in solvent inaccessible
 volume and may be expected to contribute little to the solvent distribution.
 This intermediate density representation may serve as an abstraction between
 a generic QM code and a solvent model: every electronic structure solver
 that is supposed to inter-operate with the solvent model will need to implement
 procedures to compute 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

density expansion coefficients
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $Q[n]$
\end_inset

 and their variational derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta Q/\delta n$
\end_inset

 with respect to density.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In practice one would choose elements of the density matrix as primary variables.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The force field part of the solute-solvent interaction potential is an
 additive contribution to energy and molecular forces that does not directly
 affect electronic structure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Qualitative picture of a solute-solvent interaction mediated by an intermediate
 density representation as site charges
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
If all electrons of an atom contribute 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

equally
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to the site charge interacting with the environment, the effect of the
 environment will be also 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
