 Naturally the relative position and relative orientation of two such solid
 objects is also specified by six parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fixed internal structure of the solvent molecules will be reflected
 in the form of solvent-solvent and solute-solvent interaction potential.
 A pair interaction potential is in this case a function of the six parameters
 defining relative position and orientation of the interacting parts.
 This choice 
\emph on
allows
\emph default
 but does not 
\emph on
require
\emph default
 parametrization of the solvent-solvent and solute-solvent interactions
 as e.g.
 a sum of pairwise site-site interaction terms with each site corresponding
 to an atom in a molecule or a geometric center of a charge distribution.
 The ambiguous task of constructing such a parametrization, for instance,
 from an ab-initio data set, may soon prove too tedious and not practical
 for many solute-solvent and solvent-solvent combinations.
 On the other hand an arbitrary complete sampling of an ab-initio potential
 energy surface of a isolated solute-solvent or solvent-solvent pair can
 be efficiently achieved on massively parallel architectures.
 Again the solid object model for pair interaction potential does not preclude
 the use of available site-site parametrizations of the pair interactions.
\end_layout

