\begin_layout Quote
Describes the essence of an available implementation of the BGY approach
 for three-dimensional case to build upon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The assumption of pair interactions allows one to establish a series of
 equations relating the order 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 distribution function to the order 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 distribution function 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "book:hansen76"

\end_inset

.
 The first equation of the BGY hierarchy relates the gradient of the solvent
 density to the mean field force acting on a solvent particle
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\ln g(y)=\beta\left[f_{1}(y)+\rho\int f_{2}(y,y^{\prime})g^{(2)}(y,y^{\prime})g(y^{\prime})dy\right]\label{eq:ybg-first-order}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the forces 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 are the external (solute) field and solvent-solvent interaction, respectively:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{1}(y)=-\frac{\partial u_{1}}{\partial y},\quad f_{2}(y,y^{\prime})=-\frac{\partial u_{2}(y,y^{\prime})}{\partial y};
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is a fixed parameter staying for the average solvent density.
 The BGY hierarchy of equations formalizes the stationarity condition for
 reduced distribution functions of ensembles following the classical trajectorie
s in the phase space 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "book:hansen76"

\end_inset

 and can be generalized for discrete components of the solvent parameters
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 that correspond to a mixture, Appendix
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:solvent-degrees"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equation, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ybg-first-order"

\end_inset

), is more conveniently solved for the PMF term, 
\begin_inset Formula $w(y)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\frac{\partial w}{\partial y}=\rho\int f_{2}(y,y^{\prime})g^{(2)}(y,y^{\prime})g(y^{\prime})dy,\label{eq:ybg-pmf-gradient}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

related to the distribution function by the following definition : 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(y):=g_{0}(y)\mathrm{e}^{-\beta w(y)}:=\mathrm{e}^{-\beta[u_{1}(y)+w(y)]}.
\]

\end_inset

This choice of parametrization makes the PMF contribution vanishing, 
\begin_inset Formula $w(y)\approx0$
\end_inset

, in the low density, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\approx0$
\end_inset

, or ideal gas, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\approx0$
\end_inset

, limits.
 In these limiting cases the density approaches the Boltzmann distribution
 
\begin_inset Formula $g(y)\approx g_{0}(y)$
\end_inset

.
 For mono-atomic liquids and within the RISM approach to molecular liquids
 where continuous solvent parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 correspond to a vector of three components the system of equations, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ybg-pmf-gradient"

\end_inset

), for a gradient of a scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(y)$
\end_inset

 may be replaced by a single equation relating Laplacian of the PMF term
 and divergence of the mean force field of the solvent 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "jager07diss,griebel08"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\right)^{2}w=\rho\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\int f_{2}(y,y^{\prime})g^{(2)}(y,y^{\prime})g(y^{\prime})dy^{\prime}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whereas the solvent-solvent interaction potential 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}(y,y^{\prime})$
\end_inset

 and hence the corresponding force 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}(y,y^{\prime})$
\end_inset

 depend on the relative coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $y-y^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 of a pair, the pair distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{(2)}(y,y^{\prime})$
\end_inset

 also depends on the absolute positions, 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, in the phase space of the solvent molecule due to the presence of external
 (solute) field, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}(y)$
\end_inset

.
 In fact the pair distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{(2)}$
\end_inset

 is given by the next equation in the BGY hierarchy that involves the third
 order distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{(3)}$
\end_inset

.
 The often used approach is to approximate the pair distribution function
\begin_inset Formula $g^{(2)}(y,y^{\prime})$
\end_inset

 by that of a uniform liquid with 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}=0$
\end_inset

.
 In this case it is a function of relative coordinates only: 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $g^{(2)}=g^{(2)}(y-y^{\prime})$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, the site-site distribution functions within RISM approach depend
 only on the absolute value of the distance vector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pair distribution function of the uniform liquid could be either assumed
 known from independent sources or taken from the self-consistent solution
 of the BGY equation for the analogous equation with the solute substituted
 by a solvent molecule.
 Note that the pair distribution function, 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{(2)}$
\end_inset

, and the pair force, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

, both (approximated by) a function of relative coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $y-y^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 and both parts of the model definition appear in the integral equation
 together in a product 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{f}:=f_{2}g^{(2)}$
\end_inset

.
 This antisymmetric 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weighted force
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 vector field, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{f}$
\end_inset

, together with external (solute) potential 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}$
\end_inset

 define the (approximate) model of a simple liquid completely and the BGY
 equation may be cast into the non-linear integro-differential equation:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta w=-\rho\nabla\left[\vec{f}\ast g\right],\quad g=g_{0}\mathrm{e}^{-\beta w},\label{eq:bgy3d}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with convolution integral defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a\ast b\right](x):=\int a(x-x^{\prime})b(x^{\prime})dx^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 The convolution integral, divergence of a vector field and solving the
 Laplace equation are most efficiently performed in the momentum representation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "sears03,jager07diss"

\end_inset

.
 In the momentum space the first part of the equation, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bgy3d"

\end_inset

), is an algebraic equation between the Fourier components of PMF term 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 and distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 mediated by the (Fourier components of) 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weighted force field
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{f}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k^{2}w=\mathrm{i}\rho\vec{k}\cdot\vec{f}g.
\]

\end_inset

In an iterative solution of this equation, the non-linear real space relation
 between the PMF term, 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

, and the distribution function, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bgy3d"

\end_inset

), implies repeated Fourier transformations of the PMF unknown, 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

, into the real space and an inverse transformation of the corresponding
 distribution function, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, into momentum space at each iteration 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "jager07diss"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

