\begin_layout Section
Choosing grid for position- and orientation parameters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Functions of six degrees of freedom, 
\begin_inset Formula $y=(r,q)$
\end_inset

, corresponding to a position vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, and orientation parameters, 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

, appear at a few occasions in the discussion above.
 All of the following are such functions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
solute-solvent pair interaction potential 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}(y)$
\end_inset

 where parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 define the position and orientation of a solvent molecule with respect
 to the solute in some reference orientation and location,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
solute-solvent pair distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}(y)$
\end_inset

 which corresponds to solvent distribution around solute in its reference
 orientation and location,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
solvent-solvent pair interaction potential 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}(y)$
\end_inset

 where parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 define the position and orientation of one solvent molecule with respect
 to another solvent molecule in some reference orientation and location,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
solvent-solvent pair distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{2}(y)$
\end_inset

 of a pure solvent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A discrete representation of any of these function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(y)$
\end_inset

 amounts to specifying the grid as a set of points 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{k}=(r_{k},q_{k})$
\end_inset

 and a set of corresponding values 
\begin_inset Formula $f(y_{k})$
\end_inset

.
 A particular choice is to specify the grids independently for the positions
 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and orientations 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 A uniform cartesian grid for vector 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 in the simulation cell 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{3}$
\end_inset

 is an obvious choice which has both advantages and drawbacks.
 A short range distribution function, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{2}$
\end_inset

, may quickly approach a constant at distances 
\begin_inset Formula $|r|\gg a$
\end_inset

 longer that the range parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, thus making the values in the remaining 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{3}-a^{3}$
\end_inset

 volume redundant.
 On the other hand, an equally spaced cartesian grid allows use of fast
 Fourier transformation techniques for solving integral equations for which
 there are efficient implementations available.
 For the equally spaced grid one takes for granted that for any two grid
 points 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 the difference 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}-r_{1}$
\end_inset

 is also a grid point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following discussion we assume that parameters, 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

, specifying orientation are the unit quaternions.
 The unit quaternions are often used to parametrize 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3)$
\end_inset

 rotations because of the existing homomorphism between unit quaternion
 group under multiplication and 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3)$
\end_inset

.
 This 2-to-1 correspondence (quaternions that differ by a sign map to the
 same rotation) has a nice property of being a smooth parametrization of
 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3)$
\end_inset

.
 The parameter space for unit quaternions is a three-dimensional surface
 of a sphere, 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}$
\end_inset

, embedded into the four-dimensional Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{4}$
\end_inset

 with any two opposite poles of the sphere being equivalent.
 Several choices for the (integration) grid on such a manifold exist [Stroud
 1960].
 The equivalence of the opposite poles may be enforced either by considering
 only the functions even in quaternionic parameters, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(r,q)=f(r,-q)$
\end_inset

, or by grid pruning eliminating redundant points.
 For the specialized problem at hand another aspect of the quaternion grid
 may be worth considering.
 Note that for the two species with orientations 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}$
\end_inset

 their relative orientation will be given by quaternion product 
\begin_inset Formula $q=q_{1}^{-1}q_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 It may be advantageous if this product is also a grid point if both 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}$
\end_inset

 are themselves grid points (property taken for granted for relative 
\emph on
positions
\emph default
 on uniform cartesian grids).
 Such grids are well defined as they correspond to the exhaustively studied
 point groups as subgroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(3)$
\end_inset

.
 We will also consider properties of such 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

symmetry adapted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 integration grids for solute and solvent molecules exhibiting non-trivial
 symmetry.
 The fact that several orientations of a symmetric molecule are equivalent
 allows one to reduce the domain of the quaternion orientation parameters
 on the three-dimensional sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}$
\end_inset

 to the smaller fundamental domain.
 This fundamental domain of orientation parameters is the counterpart of
 the unit cell in direct- or Brilloin zone in reciprocal space corresponding
 to translational symmetry.
 
\end_layout

